## Context

`compute_breakpoints.py` already computes cosine distance between embedding
centroids (lines 109–114) as part of the Oeconomia manuscript's breakpoint
detection. The Oeconomia parametric approach performed well. This ticket wraps
the same statistic as a proper zoo method (S0_centroid) so it appears in the
18-panel figure alongside S1–S4.

### Why this method is worth adding

Cosine centroid distance has three distinct advantages:

1. **Speed**: O(n·d) per (year, window) — compare embeddings of n papers in d=768
   dimensions just by computing two means and one dot product. No pairwise distances,
   no sorting, no kernel matrices. For n≈500, S2_energy is ~250,000 distance
   evaluations; S0 is 1,000.

2. **Analytical null (optional)**: Under the approximation that embeddings are drawn
   from an isotropic Gaussian with variance σ² per dimension, the mean vectors satisfy:
   `μ̂_b ~ N(μ, σ²I/n_b)` and `μ̂_a ~ N(μ, σ²I/n_a)`. The expected cosine between
   the two unit-normalized means under the null is 1 (same population), and the
   variance of `1 - cos(μ̂_b, μ̂_a)` is approximately:
   `Var ≈ (1/n_b + 1/n_a) · σ²/(d · ||μ||²)`
   In practice, sentence embeddings are NOT isotropic Gaussian (they concentrate on
   a manifold), so the analytical null is a first-order approximation only. The zoo
   cross-year Z-score normalization makes the analytical null unnecessary for the
   main zoo plot — the empirical normalization handles it. The analytical null
   becomes useful only if S0 is added to the permutation null model framework later.

3. **Interpretability**: cos(μ_b, μ_a) directly measures whether the "average topic"
   shifted direction in embedding space — complementary to S2_energy (distribution
   shape) and S3 (distributional transport), none of which capture the mean vector
   shift as cleanly.

### No equal-n subsampling needed

Cosine centroid distance is a function of the means, which are computed from all
papers in each window. No stochastic element — the ribbon (ticket 0105) is trivially
flat for S0. This means S0 belongs to the same deterministic tier as G3/G4/G7.

### Window convention

Use the standard zoo sliding-window convention from `_iter_window_pairs`:
- before: `[year − w, year − gap]` where gap = `div_cfg.get("gap", 1)`
- after: `[year + gap, year + w]`

This differs from `compute_breakpoints.py`'s asymmetric window
`[y−w−censor_gap, y−censor_gap]` / `[y+1, y+1+w]`. Use the zoo convention
for consistency with other sliding methods, not the breakpoints convention.

**Do not normalize embeddings before computing centroids.** Normalizing individual
vectors before averaging changes the centroid direction (it's no longer the true
mean of the distribution). Compute the raw mean vectors; then use
`scipy.spatial.distance.cosine` which handles normalization internally.

